ngland, United Kingdom","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1478–1548":"1478–1548","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1502–1557":"1502–1557","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1478":"1478","1480":"1480","1548":"1548","Manuden, Essex, England":"Manuden, Essex, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1478–1548":"1478–1548","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1502–1557":"1502–1557","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1478":"1478","1480":"1480","1548":"1548","Manuden, Essex, England":"Manuden, Essex, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Somerset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from the English county of Somerset, which takes its name from Somerton in Somerset (see   Summerton  ) + Old English <i>sǣte</i> ‘settlers, dwellers’. The <i>Somerset</i> family who are Dukes of Beaufort are descended from the Plantagenets. The surname was assumed by Charles <i>Somerset</i> (1460–1520), illegitimate son of Henry Beaufort, Duke of Somerset. The latter was himself descended illegitimately from Edward III through John of Gaunt. A later member of the family was Fitzroy <i>Somerset</i> (1788–1855), who, as Lord Raglan, was the commander of British forces in the Crimea, one of the men responsible for the charge of the Light Brigade.","possibly a habitational name from one or more places called with Old Norse <i>sumar</i> ‘summer’ + <i>sætr</i> ‘shieling, hill pasture’, such as Summerseat in Elton (Lancashire), but decisive northern early bearers are lacking."],"variants":[{"name":"Summerton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Somerton, particularly in Oxfordshire and Somerset, but also in Lincolnshire and Norfolk, named with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Summersett","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Somerset  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Joan de Somerset was born in 1478, in Wedmore, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Sir Robert Mede. She died in 1548, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1478–1548":"1478–1548","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1502–1557":"1502–1557","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1478":"1478","1480":"1480","1548":"1548","Manuden, Essex, England":"Manuden, Essex, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1478–1548":"1478–1548","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1502–1557":"1502–1557","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1478":"1478","1480":"1480","1548":"1548","Manuden, Essex, England":"Manuden, Essex, England","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1478–1548":"1478–1548","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1502–1557":"1502–1557","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1478":"1478","1480":"1480","1548":"1548","Manuden, Essex, England":"Manuden, Essex, Angleterre","Clavering, Essex, England":"Clavering, Essex, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Wedmore, Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"